First, we need to determine the type of triangle we have. We can use the Cayley-Menger determinant to find the area.
The Cayley-Menger determinant for a triangle with sides $a$, $b$, and $c$ is given by: \[
\text{Area} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{192} \left| \begin{array}{cccc} 0 & 1 & 1 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 & a^2 & b^2 \\ 1 & a^2 & 0 & c^2 \\ 1 & b^2 & c^2 & 0 \end{array} \right|}
\] Plugging in $a = 13$, $b = 17$, and $c = 12\sqrt{2}$, we get: \[
\text{Area} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{192} \left| \begin{array}{cccc} 0 & 1 & 1 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 & 169 & 289 \\ 1 & 169 & 0 & 288 \\ 1 & 289 & 288 & 0 \end{array} \right|}
\] Expanding this determinant, we get: \[
\text{Area} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{192} \cdot 338} = \sqrt{\frac{169}{96}} = \frac{13}{4\sqrt{6}}
\] <answer> $\frac{13}{4\sqrt{6}}$ </answer>

